American of Two Kinds
New York — As I write this article, officials across the United States are still counting the votes from the 2020 presidential election.
Once the results are finalized, recounts and legal challenges are sure to follow.
This is to be expected in this highly competitive election with record voter turnout.
Only American citizens can vote for the president, but this choice affects people all over the country.
If it's too early to determine the election results, then discussing the implications of this election for the world's most powerful country is not too early.
From a positive perspective, the United States remains a strong democratic nation.
Despite the practical limitations related to the pandemic, voter participation has remained high.
This process seems to be proceeding as planned.
And violent incidents have been rare.
The court is investigating the U.S. Postal Service's decision, which appears to be motivated by political reasons, hindering the transportation of ballots from areas where the majority of expected votes are from Democrats.
Current U.S. President Trump made an unfounded announcement of victory on Tuesday evening, which received little response, and his request to stop counting votes (at least in the states where he was leading) seems to have been ignored.
However, it is concerning that the division among American voters remains significant.
The votes of the two candidates are almost equal.
It is no surprise that this division is likely to lead to a split in the government.
If the current trend continues, the Democrats will win the White House and continue to control the House of Representatives, while the Republicans will continue to control the Senate.
State governorships and state legislative seats are almost evenly split between the two parties (with the Republicans having a slight advantage).
The expected "blue wave" for the Democrats did not materialize.
Biden is likely to win the popular vote by a large margin, probably securing around 4 to 5 million votes out of nearly 160 million.
However, Republicans held onto many seats that were predicted to flip, while the Democrats actually lost seats in the House of Representatives.
This outcome did not come from strong authorization, nor did it stem from political adjustments.
Trump's poll numbers are excellent, with 5 million more votes than in 2016, making him the second-highest vote-getter among all U.S. presidential candidates in history, and surpassing any previous winner.
Particularly noteworthy is that this occurred against the backdrop of record-high daily new coronavirus cases of 100,000 and over 1,000 deaths.
Just as the consequences of his government's inadequate response to the pandemic became most severe, nearly half of the voters turned to support him.
Even if Trump loses, which seems likely, he will still have strong influence, especially if he continues to remain in the public eye (which also seems likely).
Even if he himself does not run, he is likely to have a significant influence on the selection of the Republican nominee in the 2024 presidential election.
The Republican Party will be far removed from the party of former President Bush or Reagan.
Trumpism — a modern American populism — will still be a powerful force.
It is no surprise that, despite Trump having no evidence to support his claims, he desperately tries to appear virtuous and upright, attempts to undermine the legitimacy of the election results, and accuses there being voter fraud.
Many of his supporters will refuse to accept the legitimacy of Biden's presidency.
Trump is very likely never to give up, let alone attend the inauguration ceremony of his successor.
As Will Rogers once said, Trump has never encountered a norm he couldn't break.
Americans are increasingly living in different worlds.
They categorize themselves into different communities and regions based on similar views.
And each world tends to watch its own cable TV channels, listen to its own radio stations and podcasts, and visit its own websites.
The absence of a national civic curriculum has provided convenience for the differentiation of people from different generations.
It is worth emphasizing that in most cases, the division of the country is not along economic lines.
People from all social strata voted for the two candidates, and the voting patterns by population, gender, and race were not as one-sided as many had predicted.
Their main disagreement lies in the remedies.
Educational level is clearly an indicator of political orientation, as is geographic location. Republican voters tend to live in suburban and rural areas, while Democratic voters tend to live in metropolitan areas.
However, the role of culture in American politics may be greater than any other factor.
In fact, foreign policy seems to be of little importance in campaigns, except for mobilizing specific districts, such as the large Cuban and Venezuelan communities in South Florida.
In this context, it is difficult to gain public support for major reforms to the way presidential elections or government operations are conducted.
This situation is no different from the reform of the United Nations Security Council.
Many people believe that the current system has serious flaws and lacks representativeness, but it is impossible to reach a consensus on reform because any potential solution would benefit some and harm others.
It is not surprising that those who will suffer losses from the change will resist the change.
This will make governance difficult.
This largely depends on Mitch McConnell, the Republican Senate leader, and his ability and willingness to cooperate with the future Biden administration.
Cooperation also requires Biden to make compromises, which will certainly face resistance from members of his own party who are ideologically strong.
Democrats have tried to sharply dismiss everything that Trump and his representatives stand for.
But they were not successful.
Meanwhile, Republicans sought an election that would recognize Trump.
But this also did not go as they had hoped.
Instead, the election revealed a nation and two types of citizens.
They will have to coexist; but whether they can coexist remains to be seen.
